explanation:
To determine whether any statements in OS_TimerDelete are dead code you must know the semantics, return values and side-effects of the calls, the meanings of constants/modes, and the layout/usage of the objects that the function manipulates. The required symbols are:

- OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl, OS_TaskGetId_Impl: determine when the early return (OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE) can occur; needed to tell if the rest of the function is unreachable in some contexts.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: controls whether the main deletion path executes (returns OS_SUCCESS or not) and how tokens are produced; its behaviour affects whether the code inside the if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) is ever executed.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET, OS_timecb_table, OS_timebase_table: mapping from tokens to the timecb/timebase records — needed to know which fields are read/written and whether those writes are observable (i.e. not dead).
- OS_ObjectIdTransferToken: moves token ownership/reference; required to know whether subsequent operations (locks/releases/finalize) depend on this transfer (affects whether earlier assignments are necessary).
- OS_TimeBaseLock_Impl, OS_TimeBaseUnlock_Impl: establish critical-section semantics — whether writes to timebase/timecb under the lock are visible/necessary and whether locking has side effects that are required.
- OS_ObjectIdFromToken, OS_ObjectIdEqual: used for ID comparisons and assignments; their semantics determine whether comparisons/assignments can be optimized away or are observable.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: completes deletion and may read or rely on fields changed earlier (e.g. next_cb/prev_cb/timebase_token); must inspect to see if preceding field updates are required.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: releases the transferred timebase token (reference count) — needed to know whether the earlier transfer and the local timebase_token variable are needed (i.e. to avoid dead release/retain pairs).
- OS_ObjectIdDefined, OS_TimeBaseDelete: determine whether the dedicated timebase deletion at the end ever executes and whether dedicated_timebase_id initialization/assignment is necessary.
- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMECB, OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE, OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, OS_SUCCESS, OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE, OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED, TIMECB_FLAG_DEDICATED_TIMEBASE: all constant macros/enums used in conditionals and assignments — their possible values affect which branches run and whether assignments/branches are dead.
- osal_id_t, OS_object_token_t: types of ids/tokens — understanding whether tokens carry ownership or are opaque values is necessary to decide if token transfers/releases/assignments have observable effects.
- OS_timecb_internal_record_t, OS_timebase_internal_record_t: structure layouts (fields timebase_token, first_cb, next_cb, prev_cb, flags) and semantics — needed to know whether modifications to these fields are observed elsewhere (e.g., by finalize or other threads) or are redundant.

Together these symbols let an analyzer determine (a) whether each branch can be taken, (b) whether writes have observable effects (through finalize/release/delete/other tasks), and (c) whether any assignment or sequence is removable without changing program behaviour (the definition of dead code).
